<div class="container">
    <h1>Classes in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>A <strong>class</strong> is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines the properties (fields) and behaviors (methods) that the objects created from the class will have.</p>

    <h2>Defining a Class in C#</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Basic Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Creating Objects from a Class</h2>
    <p>You can create multiple objects from a single class, each with its own data:</p>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Creating Objects</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
Student student1 = new Student();
student1.Name = "Alice";
student1.Age = 20;
student1.Study();

Student student2 = new Student();
student2.Name = "Bob";
student2.Age = 22;
student2.Study();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Key Points About Classes</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>A class is a template; objects are instances of a class.</li>
        <li>Properties store object data, methods define behaviors.</li>
        <li>Access modifiers (public, private, protected) control visibility.</li>
        <li>Classes can have constructors to initialize objects (we’ll cover this next).</li>
    </ul>

